Defining parameters and variables

Ou first variable is the âdisaster_damagesâ one. We assume that disaster damages (as % of GDP) follow a right-skewed distribution (most disasters are small, but some are extreme). In fact, most events have relatively minor impacts, but a few extreme events cause significant damage (e.g., the 2011 Japan tsunami causing 5.98% of GDP damage). It has a mean of 0.1 as it is consistent with the examples in the paper where the average qualifying disaster was estimated at around 0.19% of GDP for events in the dataset. A skewness of 2 was chosen to approximate the variability and skewness observed in disaster costs as presented in the paperâs dataset.

By incorporating credit growth, the simulation tests the paperâs hypothesis that its interaction with disaster damages significantly impacts financial stability.Â The assumption about credit growth distribution was made in the simulation as a reasonable simplification, based on the idea that credit growth in economies typically fluctuates symmetrically around a mean value.

n <- 100

mean_damages <- 0.1 
skewness <- 2

disaster_damages <- rgamma(n, shape = 2, scale = mean_damages / skewness)

mean_credit_growth <- 0.03 # this is my average annual credit growth (3%)
sd_credit_growth <- 0.02 

credit_growth <- rnorm(n, mean_credit_growth, sd_credit_growth)

Crisis risk model

Assumption: Crisis risk increases with disaster damages and credit growth. We model it as a probability based on a logistic function.

The crisis risk parameters in the simulation are based on reasonable approximations aligned with the paperâs findings. The intercept (alpha=â3) sets the baseline crisis probability at approximately 4.7%, reflecting the low but non-negligible annual likelihood of financial crises historically. The coefficient for disaster damages (beta_damages =10) ensures that damages equivalent to 0.1% of GDP increase crisis probability significantly, consistent with the paperâs estimated 6â18% increase in crisis odds. The coefficient for credit growth (beta_credit =5) models its amplifying effect, reflecting findings that rapid credit expansion elevates financial instability.

alpha <- -3 
beta_damages <- 10
beta_credit <- 5
sigma_u <- 1.5

We compute the log-odds of crisis risk to model the relationship between disaster damages, credit growth, and the likelihood of a financial crisis. This approach follows the logistic regression framework. These log-odds are then transformed into probabilities using the logistic function.

log_odds_crisis <- alpha + beta_damages * disaster_damages + beta_credit * credit_growth + sigma_u
crisis_probability <- 1 / (1 + exp(-log_odds_crisis))

The crisis outcomes are simulated as a binary variable using these probabilities, reflecting whether a crisis occurred in a given period.

crisis <- rbernoulli(n, crisis_probability)

For loop

n_iter <- 100 
n <- 100 
res <- NULL 

# Simulation parameters from our model
set.seed(42)
beta_damages <- 10 # 
beta_credit <- 5   
alpha <- -3        
mean_damages <- 0.1 
skewness <- 2
mean_credit_growth <- 0.03
sd_credit_growth <- 0.02
sigma_u <- 1.5

for (i in 1:n_iter) {
  disaster_damages <- rgamma(n, shape = 2, scale = mean_damages / skewness)
  credit_growth <- rnorm(n, mean_credit_growth, sd_credit_growth)
  
  log_odds_crisis <- alpha + beta_damages * disaster_damages + beta_credit * credit_growth
  crisis_probability <- 1 / (1 + exp(-log_odds_crisis))
  crisis <- rbernoulli(n, crisis_probability)
  u <- rnorm(n, 0, sigma_u)
  
  data_sim <- tibble(
    disaster_damages,
    credit_growth,
    crisis,
    u
  )
  
  reg <- glm(crisis ~ disaster_damages + credit_growth, data = data_sim, family = binomial)
  
  coef_table <- broom::tidy(reg)
  conf_intervals <- confint(reg) 
  
  coef_table <- coef_table |> 
    mutate(
      conf.low = conf_intervals[, 1],
      conf.high = conf_intervals[, 2]
    )
  
  # Filter for terms of interest and add simulation ID
  coef_table <- coef_table |> 
    filter(term %in% c("disaster_damages", "credit_growth")) |> 
    mutate(sim_id = i)
  
  res <- bind_rows(res, coef_table)
}

âBaseâ model simulation

generate_data <- function(n,
                          alpha,
                          beta_damages,
                          beta_credit,
                          mean_damages,
                          skewness,
                          mean_credit_growth,
                          sd_credit_growth,
                          sd_error) {
  
  disaster_damages <- rgamma(n, shape = 2, scale = mean_damages / skewness)
  
  credit_growth <- rnorm(n, mean_credit_growth, sd_credit_growth)
  
  error_term <- rnorm(n, mean = 0, sd = sd_error)
  
  log_odds_crisis <- alpha + beta_damages * disaster_damages + beta_credit * credit_growth + error_term
  
  crisis_probability <- 1 / (1 + exp(-log_odds_crisis))
  
  crisis <- rbernoulli(n, crisis_probability)
  
  tibble(disaster_damages, credit_growth, crisis)
}

run_estim <- function(data) {
  glm(crisis ~ disaster_damages + credit_growth, data = data, family = binomial) |> 
    broom::tidy() |> 
    filter(term %in% c("disaster_damages", "credit_growth"))
}

compute_sim <- function(n, alpha, beta_damages, beta_credit, mean_damages, skewness, mean_credit_growth, sd_credit_growth, sd_error) {
  data <- generate_data(
    n = n,
    alpha = alpha,
    beta_damages = beta_damages,
    beta_credit = beta_credit,
    mean_damages = mean_damages,
    skewness = skewness,
    mean_credit_growth = mean_credit_growth,
    sd_credit_growth = sd_credit_growth,
    sd_error = sd_error
  )
  
  results <- run_estim(data)
  
  results |> 
    mutate(
      n = n,
      alpha = alpha,
      beta_damages = beta_damages,
      beta_credit = beta_credit,
      mean_damages = mean_damages,
      skewness = skewness,
      mean_credit_growth = mean_credit_growth,
      sd_credit_growth = sd_credit_growth,
      sd_error = sd_error
    )
}

The Credit Role Model

This simulation replicated the âcredit role modelâ described in the paper to evaluate the interaction betweenÂ disaster damagesÂ andÂ credit growthÂ in predicting financial crises. Credit growth was modeled as a separate variable and interacted with disaster damages to test whether their combined effects significantly amplify crisis risk.

generate_data <- function(n,
                          alpha,
                          beta_damages,
                          beta_credit,
                          beta_interaction,
                          beta_control,
                          mean_damages,
                          skewness,
                          mean_credit_growth,
                          sd_credit_growth,
                          mean_control,
                          sd_control,
                          sd_error) {
  
  disaster_damages <- rgamma(n, shape = 2, scale = mean_damages / skewness)
  
  credit_growth <- rnorm(n, mean_credit_growth, sd_credit_growth)
  
  control_var <- rnorm(n, mean_control, sd_control)
  
  error_term <- rnorm(n, mean = 0, sd = sd_error)
  
  log_odds_crisis <- alpha +
    beta_damages * disaster_damages +
    beta_credit * credit_growth +
    beta_interaction * disaster_damages * credit_growth +
    beta_control * control_var +
    error_term
  
  crisis_probability <- 1 / (1 + exp(-log_odds_crisis))
  
  crisis <- rbernoulli(n, crisis_probability)
  
  tibble(
    disaster_damages,
    credit_growth,
    control_var,
    crisis
  )
}

compute_sim <- function(n, alpha, beta_damages, beta_credit, beta_interaction, beta_control, 
                        mean_damages, skewness, mean_credit_growth, sd_credit_growth,
                        mean_control, sd_control, sd_error) {
  
  data <- generate_data(
    n = n,
    alpha = alpha,
    beta_damages = beta_damages,
    beta_credit = beta_credit,
    beta_interaction = beta_interaction,
    beta_control = beta_control,
    mean_damages = mean_damages,
    skewness = skewness,
    mean_credit_growth = mean_credit_growth,
    sd_credit_growth = sd_credit_growth,
    mean_control = mean_control,
    sd_control = sd_control,
    sd_error = sd_error
  )
  
  results <- glm(crisis ~ disaster_damages + credit_growth + disaster_damages:credit_growth + control_var, 
                 data = data, family = binomial) |> 
    broom::tidy()
  
  results |> 
    mutate(
      n = n,
      alpha = alpha,
      beta_damages = beta_damages,
      beta_credit = beta_credit,
      beta_interaction = beta_interaction,
      beta_control = beta_control,
      mean_damages = mean_damages,
      skewness = skewness,
      mean_credit_growth = mean_credit_growth,
      sd_credit_growth = sd_credit_growth,
      mean_control = mean_control,
      sd_control = sd_control,
      sd_error = sd_error
    )
}

Test for Omitted Variables

Full Model

In this simulation, we modeled the effect ofÂ disaster damagesÂ andÂ credit growthÂ on the probability of a financial crisis, including both variables in the regression. Credit growth was simulated as a function of disaster damages plus an error term, reflecting how disasters can influence financial conditions. This simulation tested the independent effects of both variables while accounting for their interaction. The goal was to validate the importance of including both factors, as hypothesized in the paper, and to observe how they jointly impact crisis risk.

generate_data <- function(n, alpha, beta_damages, beta_credit, sd_error) {
  disaster_damages <- rgamma(n, shape = 2, scale = 0.1)
  
  credit_growth <- 0.02 + 0.5 * disaster_damages + rnorm(n, mean = 0, sd = sd_error)
  
  log_odds_crisis <- alpha +
    beta_damages * disaster_damages +
    beta_credit * credit_growth
  
  crisis_probability <- 1 / (1 + exp(-log_odds_crisis))
  
  crisis <- rbernoulli(n, crisis_probability)
  
  tibble(
    disaster_damages,
    credit_growth,
    crisis
  )
}

beta_credit <- 5

Omitted variable test

Fiscal Capacity

This simulation extended the model by includingÂ fiscal capacityÂ as a mitigating factor in the relationship between disaster damages, credit growth, and crisis probability. Fiscal capacity was simulated first as a normally distributed variable, influencing credit growth and directly reducing crisis risk. The interaction between disaster damages and credit growth was also included. This model tested whether fiscal capacity plays a significant role in buffering against financial crises, as suggested by its institutional and economic importance.

generate_data <- function(n,
                          alpha,
                          beta_damages,
                          beta_credit,
                          beta_control,
                          mean_damages,
                          skewness,
                          h_0,
                          h_1,
                          sd_credit_shock,
                          sd_fiscal_capacity,
                          mean_control,
                          sd_control,
                          sd_error) {
  disaster_damages <- rgamma(n, shape = 2, scale = mean_damages / skewness)
  
  raw_fiscal_capacity <- rgamma(n, shape = 2, scale = sd_fiscal_capacity)
  fiscal_capacity <- raw_fiscal_capacity / (max(raw_fiscal_capacity) + 0.01)
  
  credit_growth <- h_0 + h_1 * fiscal_capacity + rnorm(n, 0, sd_credit_shock)
  
  control_var <- rnorm(n, mean_control, sd_control)
  
  error_term <- rnorm(n, mean = 0, sd = sd_error)
  
  log_odds_crisis <- alpha +
    beta_damages * disaster_damages +
    beta_control * control_var +
    error_term
  
  crisis_probability <- 1 / (1 + exp(-log_odds_crisis))
  crisis <- rbernoulli(n, crisis_probability)
  
  tibble(
    disaster_damages,
    fiscal_capacity,
    credit_growth,
    control_var,
    crisis
  )
}

baseline_param <- tibble(

compute_sim <- function(n, alpha, beta_damages, beta_credit, beta_control,
                        mean_damages, skewness, h_0, h_1, sd_credit_shock, sd_fiscal_capacity,

    beta_damages = beta_damages,
    beta_credit = beta_credit,

    mean_control = mean_control,

    sd_error = sd_error
  )

      sd_error = sd_error
    )
}
